******
[3]
Date: Wed 18 Feb 2004
Source: The Nation [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/home/2004/02/18/national/Dusit-Zoo-may-reopen-this-week-says-Prapat-93773.html>


Dusit Zoo might be reopened this week [week of 18 Feb 2004] if lab
checks find no fresh outbreak of bird flu among the crows that use
the zoo for nesting, Natural Resources and Environment Minister
Prapat Panyachatraksa said yesterday [17 Feb 2004]. "The zoo has been
shut down for over 20 days, causing hardship for animals and humans
alike," he said.

Prapat warned against hasty reaction to the spread of bird flu among
wild and migrating birds, saying the situation had not spiralled out
of control as feared. "None of the pigeons that fly over Bangkok's
skies have been found to be infected with bird flu," he said.

The country's largest lake, Bung Boraphet in Nakhon Sawan, was
declared under quarantine on Monday [16 Feb 2004] after 17 out of
more than 10 000 migrating openbill storks died from the virus, he
said. Migrating storks in the Wat Pailom sanctuary in Pathum Thani
have not been infected with the deadly virus, although a few in a
separate flock at Bangkok's Lat Krabang district have been. Livestock
officials have been conducting daily checks on bird sanctuaries and
have found about 30 percent of dead bird carcasses could be
attributed to bird flu.

