******
[4]
Date: Sat 5 Feb 2005
Source: China Economic Net, Xinhua News Agency report [edited]
<http://en.ce.cn/World/Asia-Pacific/200502/05/t20050205_3045122.shtml>


Hundreds of wild birds have died of avian influenza in the central
province of Nakhon Sawan of Thailand in a little over 2 weeks, the
Wildlife Conservation Division disclosed.

Director Chawal Thalhikorn was quoted by the Thai News Agency as
saying Saturday [5 Feb 2005] that his organization had been
monitoring the bird flu situation among wild birds closely. He said
between 18 Jan and 3 Feb [2005], almost 500 openbill storks had been
found dead at the Boraphet reservoir, Thailand's largest freshwater
swamp. Officials had burned the carcasses and sprayed disinfectant to
prevent the spread of disease.

In other control efforts, the director said more than 6800 birds from
80 species in 7 provinces had been tested for the deadly H5N1 strain
of the virus. The result of the tests will be disclosed soon.

However, he said testing by other agencies had found the bird flu
virus in 11 samples collected from 4 central provinces, including
Sukhothai, Uthai Thani, Lopburi, and Chachoengsao.

